library(ggplot2)

hdd0318cy <- read_sas("hdd0318cy.sas7bdat", 
    NULL)

Creating a subset with 10 variables

y=hdd0318cy %>% 
  select(sex,age,admtype,preopday,los,service,payer,race,yod,tot,yoa,moa)

Data cleaning

y=y %>% 
  filter_all(~!is.na(.)) %>% 
  filter_all(~!(.=='')) %>% 
  filter(sex!="9")
y1=y %>% 
  group_by(yoa) %>% 
  summarise(mean_age=mean(age)) %>% 
  mutate(mean_age=round(mean_age,0))

PLOT 1

ggplot(y1,aes(yoa,mean_age))+
  geom_line()+
  geom_text(aes(label=mean_age))

PLOT 2

ggplot(y,aes(sex))+
  geom_bar(position='dodge')

PLOT 3

ggplot(y,aes(service))+
  geom_bar(position='dodge')

10 = Medicine This is the most needed service in hospital

PLOT 4

y2=y %>% 
  group_by(yoa) %>% 
  summarise(mean_los=mean(los)) %>% 
  mutate(centered_mean=mean(mean_los)) %>% 
  mutate(sd=mean_los-centered_mean) %>% 
  mutate(sd_level=ifelse(sd>0,"above","below"))

ggplot(y2, aes(x=reorder(yoa,sd), y=sd)) +
  geom_bar(stat='identity', aes(fill=sd_level), width=0.5) +
  scale_fill_manual(name="Standarized mean length of stay for each year patients",
  labels = c("Above Average", "Below Average"),
  values = c("above"="#00ba38", "below"="#f8766d")) +
  labs(subtitle="Normalised average length of stay from 'hdd0318cy'",
  title= "Diverging Bars") +
  coord_flip()

patients went to hospital in 2004 and 2015 spend more days in hospital comparing to the average.

PLOT 5

y3=y %>%

  summarise(mean_los=mean(los))
ggplot(y3,aes(yoa,mean_los,fill=admtype))+

PLOT 9

C=y %>% 
  group_by(moa,payer,sex) %>% 
  summarise(mean_los=mean(los))


ggplot(C,aes(payer,mean_los,fill=sex))+
  geom_col()+
  transition_states(moa)+
  labs(subtitle="Different payers will results different length of stay in classification of Month and Sex", title= labs(title = 'Month of Admission = {closest_state}'))

Y is insurance payer missing, so we ignore it first. Due to unknown reasons that people who probably pay it by themselves stay longer in the hospital. Most of them are females. 2=female 1 = Medicaid insurance company provides insurant longer stay time in hospital. So, Question? Is Medicaid actually providing low-cost insurance coverage to people?

PLOT 10

D = y %>% 
  group_by(payer,sex,moa) %>% 
  summarise(mean_cost=mean(tot))
ggplot(D,aes(payer,mean_cost,fill=sex)) +
  geom_col()+
  transition_states(moa)+
  labs(subtitle="Different payers will results different cost to stay in hospital in classification of sex and month", title= labs(title = 'Month of Admission = {closest_state}'))

You can see Medicaid company pays the most comparing to other companies. Conclucion: Medicaid company is a very competitive insurance company which provides long time service of coverage, also cover a lot of payment.

cleaned_y=y %>%

  filter(age<110)

  geom_point()
